	<div class="posts">
	<a name="107272069625364830">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<h1>Computing Milieux</h1>I thought there was a way to specify categories on my Blogs.&nbsp; If so, I don't know where that is.&nbsp; It might not be here.<h2>Personal Computing</h2>Security is a general term in the ACM Computing Classification System.&nbsp; I have in mind, right now, something about security and the problem of Spam and such.<h3>The hard way to handle Spam and MalMail</h3>I have been struggling with two things: browser security and e-e-mail filtering.  I just finished reading Bruce Schneier's <em>Beyond Fear</em> and have many ideas and notes, but no solution.  <br /><br />With regard to browser security and the problems of trust regarding ActiveX, plug-ins, and whatnot, I have the following:<ul><li>A software firewall -- Zone Alarm Pro -- that watches what comes in and what goes out</li><br /><li>A malware detector -- SpyBot Search & Destroy -- that finds odd things that end up lying around on my machine without invitation</li><li>Internet Explorer 6 security and privacy settings set as high as I can stand it<br /></ul>One of my insights about all of this is that most (but not all) uses of ActiveX controls have nothing whatever to do with presentation of content and have everything to do with advertising.&nbsp; There are also situations where, if I want particular functionality (like using MSN Messenger), then I have to not check for expiration of certificates (?!) because my sign-on will fail if I do.&nbsp; I believe this is an interaction case, but it leaves me frustrated.&nbsp; I would like to be able to shut off ActiveX and other plug-ins, rather than be asked about them, my current setting.&nbsp; But there are sites where I want to allow plug-ins and I can't declare them to be trusted for that in my browser.  Thats because the designer of my browser thinks a trusted site is one that uses an SSL connection (a nice example of design by hacking, now that I think of it: If you can't solve the real problem, do something stupid instead because we have to put something at this place in the implementation [;<).&nbsp; I have a workaround in mind, but I haven't confirmed it yet.&nbsp; Meanwhile, ...<br /><br />With regard to MalMail, I have<ul><li>Firewall settings that effectively quarantines potentially-malicious attachments by renaming them,</li><li>Antivirus settings that watch my POP3 accesses and will quarantine anything that gets past the Firewall filter and also block what are considered to be malicious scripts,</li><li>Outlook 2000 settings (thanks to Office SP3 and other updates) that make malicious attachments difficult to receive at all, and</li><li>spam filtering and the junk mail tool running, along with some in-box filtering rules that I keep expanding myself.</ul>This all works pretty well except for the spam and junk situation.&nbsp; I have filters that quarantine a lot of material.&nbsp; But each week, more material escapes the filter.&nbsp; I keep reclassifying incoming mail before I delete it, and I keep reviewing the quarantine list for false rejections that are something that I actually want to receive.&nbsp; So I have an exception list and an ever-growing list of rejection cases.  The rejection cases involve words to look for (the sort of thing that a Bayesean filter might handle better) as well as source e-mail addresses.<br /><h3>The how not do do it</h3>I have been doing this backwards.&nbsp;  Instead of having to keep coming up with new barriers to an expanding tide of malmail and ActiveX and plug-in usages that don't do anything for me, I should turn it around.&nbsp;  I get proportionally less and less mail that is meant for me.&nbsp;  I have few sites where I actually want plug-ins to run.&nbsp; I need to reverse the general and special cases.<br /><br />Stay tuned ...<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#107272069625364830">Monday, December 29, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="107271978047834118">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<h1>Computing Milieux</h1>I am  making a slight effort to work within the ACM Computing Classification System.&nbsp; It is not that easy.&nbsp; But "Computing Milieux" is a topic that I recall from when I first saw the classification scheme around the time that Jean Sammet started Computing Reviews.&nbsp; Maybe this will help, maybe it will get in the way, we will see.&nbsp; I can use these for categories as well, I think.<h2>Situated Computing</h2>This theme is about situation of computation in human activities and experience, in our scientific and mathematical theories, and so on.&nbsp; I am still refining my thoughts about that.<h3>Hacking as Mindless Design</h3>It has finally occured to me that there is another way that "hacking" has an unpleasant quality.&nbsp; I don't mean the exploratory, experimental form of it, but the aspect of hacking that leads to failures of design.&nbsp; One might even say that there is no design.&nbsp; A way to tell if a piece of software is a hack in this sense is to see if one can abstract from it a model that it is intended to be an interpretation for.&nbsp; This will be an assessment, of course, but the question will be how close can one come to identifying a coherent interpretation.&nbsp; The next question is, where does it shear.&nbsp; That is, what are its failure aspects.&nbsp; In my musings on situated computing, I realized that I cannot willingly create a hack, so how can I illustrate this phenomenon?&nbsp; My thinking, this morning, is that I should create exercises, perhaps in discussing design and software engineering, where the student is invited to find some code of theirs, of their peers, or of some open-source creation, and reverse-hack it.&nbsp; This will serve to find examples of when some piece of software has been completely divorced from a purposive reality and has become a solution to a problem (or oversight) for the programmer, not of an understandable usage situation.&nbsp; This can deal with "situating" by demonstrating that software can be produced on purpose for a purpose, and the intended purpose can be well thought out and harmoniously realized.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#107271978047834118">Monday, December 29, 2003</a></span></div>
